  "output": "I read through the full codebase (~1,500 lines, pure Python — `store.py`, `fetchers.py`, `models.py`, `filters.py`, `notify.py`, `pipeline.py`, `agent.py`). One note up front: **there's no React/JS frontend anywhere in this repo** (only `.venv` package internals matched the earlier file glob) — it's a Python job-scraping pipeline, so I'm skipping that section rather than inventing findings.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (the real one)\n\n`Store.diff()` runs one `SELECT` **per job**, in a Python loop, followed by one `INSERT`/`UPDATE` per job:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nWith `fetch_all` pulling thousands of listings per run (Microsoft/Amazon alone default to `max_pages=40` × 10/page), this is thousands of round-trip statement executions where one bulk read + a single `executemany` would do.\n\n**Fix:**\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            touched.append(job.key)\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    if new:\n        cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (...)\",\n                         [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    if changed:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\",\n                         [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                         [(now, k) for k in touched])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\nThis turns O(n) round trips into O(1) bulk reads + 3 batched writes.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-27` (the clearest win)\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` recompiles the include/exclude regex lists **from scratch on every single call**:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every job\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiled every job\n```\n\nFor N jobs this recompiles the same patterns N times. `re.compile` isn't free, and Python's internal regex cache won't save you here because the pattern strings are rebuilt via `re.escape(w)` each time (different `re.Pattern` objects, cache misses accumulate function-call overhead regardless).\n\n**Fix — compile once, pass compiled patterns down:**\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, locations=None, cutoff=None):\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `models.py:65-69`, double-hashing changed jobs\n\n`Job.content_hash` is a plain `@property` (recomputed on every access, not cached). In `Store.diff()`, for a **changed** job it's computed once for the comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and then computed *again* inside `_update()` → `to_row()`. Cheap individually (sha256 over a short string), but free to fix:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _content_hash: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._content_hash is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._content_hash = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode(\"utf-8\")).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._content_hash\n```\n(`functools.cached_property` won't work directly since the class uses `slots=True` without `__dict__`; add an explicit slot as above, or drop `slots=True`.) Low priority — only worth doing alongside the `diff()` batching rewrite above, since that rewrite is what determines how many times `to_row()`/`content_hash` actually get called per job.\n\n## 4. Caching opportunity — Meta fetcher re-fetches a full HTML page every run just for tokens\n\n`fetch_meta` (`fetchers.py:537-574`) does a full `GET` of `metacareers.com/jobs` (a real marketing page) on *every* run solely to scrape `lsd`/`__spin_*` tokens before the actual GraphQL POST. Given this now runs on a 12h schedule (per commit `6ae8083`), that's a full page download twice a day purely for token extraction. Not worth caching aggressively since these tokens are session-scoped and may rotate, but worth flagging — a short-TTL (e.g. 5 min) in-process cache of the scraped tokens would save a request if `run()` is ever invoked multiple times in one process lifetime. Low priority as-is since each CLI invocation is a fresh process.\n\n## 5. Memory leaks — none found\n\nThis is a short-lived CLI (`pipeline.run_sync` / `agent.py`), not a long-running server, so classic \"leak\" patterns (growing caches, unclosed listeners) don't really apply. I checked the two places that would matter:\n- `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:767-788`): owns/closes its `httpx.AsyncClient` in a `try/finally` — correct.\n- `Store` (`store.py:35-53`): used via `with Store(...) as store:` everywhere it's constructed — connection is always closed.\n\nOnly a soft note: `fetch_all` gathers **all** sources' results fully into memory before `fetch_jobs` returns (`asyncio.gather` on every source), so peak memory is O(total jobs across all boards) held at once. Given the largest boards are capped at `max_pages≈40 × 10/page` = 400 jobs, this is a non-issue at current scale — flagging only in case sources are added at much larger scale in the future.\n\n## 6. Minor — synchronous network calls block the event loop\n\n`pipeline.run()` is `async def`, but `dispatch()` (`notify.py:105`) calls `httpx.post(...)` **synchronously** for Slack/webhook/email/SMS. Since this happens after `await fetch_all(...)` has already completed and nothing else is scheduled concurrently at that point, it's harmless today — but if `run()` is ever called concongruently with other async work in the same process, these calls would block the loop. Not worth touching unless that changes.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order if you want me to implement:** #1 (`store.py` batching) is the highest-value fix since it scales with job count; #2 (`filters.py` regex compile) is a quick, zero-risk win. Want me to apply either?\n",
